            <section class="prose">
              <h2>What is House Rent Allowance (HRA)?</h2>
              <p>
                House Rent Allowance (HRA) is a component of your salary paid by
                your employer to help you meet rental expenses. Under
                <strong>Section 10(13A)</strong> of the Income Tax Act, a part
                of this HRA can be <strong>exempt from tax</strong> if:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>You are a <strong>salaried employee</strong>, and</li>
                <li>
                  You actually live in <strong>rented accommodation</strong>,
                  and
                </li>
                <li>You receive HRA as part of your salary structure.</li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                The exempt portion is calculated using three rule‑based limits.
                The remaining HRA, if any, is taxable and added to your income
                from salary.
              </p>

              <h2>HRA Exemption Formula – The Three Rule‑Based Limits</h2>
              <p>
                For the relevant period (usually the financial year), compute
                these three amounts:
              </p>

              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <ol class="list-decimal">
                  <li><strong>Actual HRA received</strong> from employer.</li>
                  <li>
                    <strong>50% of (Basic + DA)</strong> if you live in a
                    <strong>metro city</strong> (Delhi, Mumbai, Kolkata,
                    Chennai), or <strong>40% of (Basic + DA)</strong> for
                    <strong>non‑metro</strong> cities.
                  </li>
                  <li><strong>Rent paid − 10% of (Basic + DA)</strong>.</li>
                </ol>
                <p class="mt-2 mb-0">
                  <strong>HRA exemption = Minimum of (1), (2), and (3)</strong>
                </p>
              </div>

              <p>
                If <strong>rent paid ≤ 10% of (Basic + DA)</strong>, then the
                third amount becomes zero or negative, and
                <strong>no HRA exemption</strong> is available for that period.
              </p>

              <h3>Important points about the formula</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Use
                  <strong
                    >Basic + DA that forms part of retirement benefits</strong
                  >
                  (not all allowances).
                </li>
                <li>
                  Calculations should ideally be done
                  <strong>month‑wise</strong> if salary, rent or city changes
                  during the year.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Metro vs non‑metro status is based on the
                  <strong>location of the rented house</strong>, not your
                  permanent address.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Step‑by‑step: How to calculate your HRA exemption</h2>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  <strong>Collect your salary details</strong><br />
                  Note your monthly basic salary, DA (if applicable), and HRA
                  received from your employer.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Note your rent and city type</strong><br />
                  Add up the rent you actually pay and check if your rented
                  house is in a metro or non‑metro city.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Compute the three rule‑based amounts</strong><br />
                  Use the formulas above or the calculator on this page.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Take the least of the three</strong><br />
                  That least amount is your <strong>HRA exemption</strong>. The
                  balance HRA, if any, is taxable.
                </li>
              </ol>

              <h2>Worked example: HRA calculation for a salaried individual</h2>
              <p>Assume the following for the full year (12 months):</p>
              <ul>
                <li>Basic salary: ₹50,000 per month</li>
                <li>
                  DA (forming part of retirement benefits): ₹5,000 per month
                </li>
                <li>HRA received: ₹20,000 per month</li>
                <li>Rent paid: ₹18,000 per month</li>
                <li>City: Bengaluru (non‑metro)</li>
              </ul>

              <p><strong>Step 1 – Convert to annual figures</strong></p>
              <ul>
                <li>Basic + DA = ₹55,000 per month → ₹6,60,000 per year</li>
                <li>HRA received = ₹20,000 per month → ₹2,40,000 per year</li>
                <li>Rent paid = ₹18,000 per month → ₹2,16,000 per year</li>
              </ul>

              <p><strong>Step 2 – Compute the three amounts</strong></p>
              <ol>
                <li>Actual HRA received = <strong>₹2,40,000</strong></li>
                <li>
                  40% of (Basic + DA) for non‑metro = 40% × ₹6,60,000 =
                  <strong>₹2,64,000</strong>
                </li>
                <li>
                  Rent paid − 10% of (Basic + DA) = ₹2,16,000 − 10% × ₹6,60,000
                  = ₹2,16,000 − ₹66,000 = <strong>₹1,50,000</strong>
                </li>
              </ol>

              <p><strong>Step 3 – Take the least of the three</strong></p>
              <p>
                The three values are ₹2,40,000; ₹2,64,000; and ₹1,50,000. The
                <strong>least</strong> is <strong>₹1,50,000</strong>.
              </p>
              <p>
                So, <strong>HRA exemption = ₹1,50,000</strong> and
                <strong>Taxable HRA = ₹2,40,000 − ₹1,50,000 = ₹90,000</strong>.
              </p>

              <h2>Common edge cases and practical tips</h2>
              <h3>1. If your rent is low compared to salary</h3>
              <p>
                When rent paid is close to or below 10% of (Basic + DA), the
                third amount becomes very small or zero. In such cases,
                <strong>HRA exemption may be minimal or nil</strong>, even if
                you receive a large HRA.
              </p>

              <h3>2. Changing city or rent mid‑year</h3>
              <p>
                If you move from a non‑metro to a metro city (or vice versa), or
                your rent/salary changes during the year, you should ideally:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Compute HRA exemption
                  <strong>separately for each period</strong> with consistent
                  values, and
                </li>
                <li>
                  Add up the exemptions for all periods to get the annual
                  exemption.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>3. HRA under the new tax regime</h3>
              <p>
                Under the <strong>new tax regime (Section 115BAC)</strong>, HRA
                exemption under Section 10(13A) is
                <strong>not available</strong>. This calculator is therefore
                relevant only if you opt for the
                <strong>old tax regime</strong>.
              </p>

              <h2>Documents required to claim HRA exemption</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Rent receipts</strong> (monthly/quarterly) signed by
                  the landlord.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Rent agreement</strong> (recommended, especially for
                  higher rents).
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Landlord’s PAN</strong> if annual rent exceeds
                  ₹1,00,000.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Proof of payment such as
                  <strong>bank statements, UPI records, or cheques</strong>.
                </li>
                <li>
                  HRA declaration form or proof as required by your employer.
                </li>
              </ul>
