              <h2>FAQs on HRA calculation and exemption</h2>

              <h3>Can self‑employed individuals claim HRA?</h3>
              <p>
                No. HRA exemption under Section 10(13A) is available only to
                salaried individuals who receive HRA from an employer.
                Self‑employed individuals may explore deduction under
                <strong>Section 80GG</strong> if they pay rent and satisfy the
                prescribed conditions.
              </p>

              <h3>Can I claim both home loan interest and HRA?</h3>
              <p>
                Yes, in certain situations. For example, if you own a house in
                one city (on which you are paying home loan EMIs) but live in a
                rented house in another city for work, you may be able to claim:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>HRA exemption for the rented house, and</li>
                <li>
                  Interest deduction under Section 24(b) and principal deduction
                  under Section 80C for the home loan.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                However, if you live in your own house, HRA exemption is
                generally not available.
              </p>

              <h3>Is PAN of landlord mandatory?</h3>
              <p>
                If your <strong>annual rent exceeds ₹1,00,000</strong>, your
                employer will typically ask for the
                <strong>PAN of the landlord</strong>. If the landlord does not
                have a PAN, a declaration to that effect may be required.
              </p>

              <h3>Can I claim HRA if I pay rent to my spouse?</h3>
              <p>
                Tax authorities often scrutinise such arrangements closely. If
                the property is owned by your spouse and you pay rent, the
                arrangement must be
                <strong>genuine and commercially reasonable</strong>, with
                actual transfer of rent and declaration of rental income by your
                spouse. Many tax professionals advise caution in such cases.
              </p>
